Eleanor Holmes Norton, D-D.C., a co-chair of the caucus, said that "black men today are clothed in stereotypes, as youth and finally as men." That sentiment was echoed by Michael Eric Dyson, the author of "Debating Race" and a sociology professor at Georgetown University, who argued that all black men live under suspicion, as evidenced by racial profiling, higher rates of incarceration and school expulsions for young black men.
